A major downside of the singleton instance is that it precludes any
configurability. For a real-world example: the Git plugin will probably
allow the user to configure diff settings, like a change is a complete
rewrite if more than 70% of the file is changed, or ignore end-of-line
whitespace, or try harder to detect copies (these are all real
options to `git diff`).

It is reasonable to expect that these options can affect how the
porcelain behaves. Suppose that the Git plugin stores becomes edges
with a payload of `{rewriteProportion: number}`. Then we might have code
like the following:

```js
class TreeEntryReference extends /*  */ {
  _options: GitPluginOptions;
  constructor(base: NodeReference, options: GitPluginOptions) {
    super(base);
    this._options = options;
  }
  *becomes(): Iterator<TreeEntryReference> {
    for (const neighbor of this.neighbors({})) {
      const {rewriteProportion} = neighbor.edge.payload;
      const {rewriteThreshold} = this._options;
      if (rewriteProportion >= rewriteThreshold) {
        // This change counts as a rewrite: theres no edge.
        continue;
      }
      yield /*  */;
    }
  }
}
class GitPluginHandler implements PluginHandler {
  _options: GitPluginOptions;
  constructor(options: GitPluginOptions) {
    this._options = options;
  }
  pluginName() { return GIT_PLUGIN_NAME; }
  createReference(base: NodeReference) {
    switch (base.address.type) {
      case TREE_ENTRY_NODE_TYPE:
        return new TreeEntryReference(base, this._options);
      // 
    }
  }
  // 
}
```

In this case, attempting to merge graphs with Git plugin handlers with
different settings seems like it _must_ be an error, because any result
would fail to be a conservative extension of the original graphs.

Given that configurability of algorithms and plugins is an important
design goal, Id prefer to think about this more carefully rather than
to just pick something thats easy to implement and ship it. If you want
to get something in quickly so that we can finish up this redesign and
move onto more critical-path things, then Id be happy to put in
something that is actually conservative: one option is the code in this
PR, which shifts the responsibility to the caller; another option is
using reference equality as the congruence, which (while conservative)
is bad for configurability and requires plugins to provide instance
control. As you might infer, I favor the former option.

